06620nam a22009615i 9780812201376DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20132004pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122013767 a10.9783/97808122013762doi  a(DE-B1597)448990  a(OCoLC)979630902  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aDU740.42b.W65 2004eb 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a390/.0995322200aWomen as Unseen Characters :bMale Ritual in Papua New Guinea /ced. by Pascale Bonnemère. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2013] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSocial Anthropology in Oceania00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tNote for Readers -- tIntroduction. The Presence of Women in New Guinea Secret Male Rituals: From Ritual Space to Ritual Process -- t1. Sambia Womens Positionality and Men's Rituals -- t2. Embodiments of Detachment: Engendering Agency in the Highlands of Papua New Guinea -- t3. When Women Enter the Picture: Looking at Anga Initiations from the Mothers' Angle -- t4. Ujawe: The Ritual Transformation of Sons and Mothers -- t5. The Bachelors and Their Spirit Wife: Interpreting the Omatisia Ritual of Porgera and Paiela -- t6. Cults, Closures, Collaborations -- t7. The Variability of Women's Involvement" in Anga Male Initiations -- t8. Of Human and Spirit Women: From Mother to Seductress to Second Wife -- t9. Relating to Women: Female Presence in Melanesian ”Male Cults" -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRituals have always been a focus of ethnographies of Melanesia, providing a ground for important theorizing in anthropology. This is especially true of the male initiation rituals that until recently were held in Papua New Guinea. For the most part, these rituals have been understood as all-male institutions, intended to maintain and legitimate male domination. Women's exclusion from the forest space where men conducted most such rites has been taken as a sign of their exclusion from the entire ritual process.Women as Unseen Characters is the first book to examine the role of females in Papua New Guinea male rituals, and the first systematic treatment of this issue for any part of the world. In this volume, leading Melanesian scholars build on recent ethnographies that show how female kin had roles in male rituals that had previously gone unseen. Female seclusion and the enforcement of taboos were crucial elements of the ritual process: forms of presence in their own right.Contributors here provide detailed accounts of the different kinds of female presence in various Papua New Guinea male rituals. When these are restored to the picture, the rituals can no longer be interpreted merely as an institution for reproducing male domination but must also be understood as a moment when the whole system of relations binding a male person to his kin is reorganized. By dealing with the participation of women, a totally neglected dimension of male rituals is added to our understanding.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aHamtai (Papua New Guinean people)xRites and ceremonies. 0aSambia (Papua New Guinean people)xRites and ceremonies. 0aWomen, SambiaxAttitudes. 0aWomen, SambiaxSocial conditions. 4aFolklore. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aAnthropology.  aFolklore.  aGender Studies.  aLinguistics.  aWomen's Studies.1 aBamford, Sandra C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBiersack, Aletta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonnemère, Pascale, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb